  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a Trie-based optimization problem. To avoid identity theft, no ID can be a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that in a Trie containing all final IDs, no leaf node is an ancestor of another leaf node. We need to find the minimum bits to add to make all strings 'prefix-free'.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_construction_and_prefix_analysis",
      "instructions": "Construct a Trie from the given N bitstrings. For each node in the Trie, track whether it represents the end of one of the original IDs. Identify all nodes that are 'terminal' (end of an original ID). For each terminal node, determine if it is an ancestor of another terminal node in the original set. This identifies the initial 'identity theft' conflicts."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_cost_optimization_logic",
      "instructions": "Given a Trie where some nodes are marked as terminal, we need to add bits to each terminal node such that no terminal node is a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that for every terminal node, all its descendants in the Trie are not terminal, and it itself is not a prefix of any other terminal node. Formulate a greedy strategy or dynamic programming approach to calculate the minimum bits to add. Specifically, if a terminal node has descendants that are also terminal, we must extend the current terminal node or its descendants to ensure they are unique. The cost is the sum of bits added to each string."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will take the Trie structure and the conflict information from helper 1. It will then apply the optimization logic from helper 2 to calculate the minimum number of bits required to resolve all prefix conflicts. The final answer is the sum of the lengths of the added bit sequences."
}

